  "text": "In an example force-extension retraction curve, where a single polyprotein is adsorbed onto the cantilever tip, the polyprotein is elongated and the force acting on each protein domain increases as the cantilever is moved away from the substrate [ Fig. 1(b) ]. At a given force, one of the domains will unfold, resulting in a peak in the force-extension trace. This unfolding event releases previously sequestered polypeptide, slackening the chain, which results in a sudden decrease in force seen in the force-extension trace, followed by a gradual increase in force again as the distance between the cantilever and the substrate continually increases. As each domain in the chain unfolds, each unfolding event appears as a peak in the resulting sawtooth pattern. This process is stochastic, and it is not possible to predict the order in which a chain of identical domains will unfold [CITATION_1] .The final peak in every force versus extension trace is the detachment peak, which is not included in the analysis.",
